snippet.textDisplay: He makes it look so easy, but when I made the shortbread (JUST the shortbread) I used salted butter. So when I was pressing the dough into the pan and decided to treat myself with a nibble, the morsel was next level salty. I decided to dilute the batch with ANOTHER batch, but this one with no salt. I combined the two, repressed them into my pan, and once I started docking the dough, I realized: I didn't use a spring form. How the hell am I going to get the effing thing out? I decided I didn't care and stuck the damn thing in the oven. I have roughly 10 minutes before I realize the true gravitas of my mistaje. Luckily, I am alone this Valentine's day, (probably because I lack the necessary domestic skills a lady needs) so I am not trying to impress anyone. And between you and me, I'm probably going to eat the whole pan by myself, so whatever. So take note: if you too are a fool, don't expect it to be so easy. Great vid otherwise.

snippet.textDisplay: For anyone complaining about tempering chocolate, an easy and fool proof way to do it is with a sous vide machine if you have one. Heat the water to 115, melt you chocolate in a bag, then cool the chocolate to 95 by putting ice cubes in the water. Let the chocolate sit in the 95 degree water for about 15 minutes for it to come to temp.
snippet.textOriginal: For anyone complaining about tempering chocolate, an easy and fool proof way to do it is with a sous vide machine if you have one. Heat the water to 115, melt you chocolate in a bag, then cool the chocolate to 95 by putting ice cubes in the water. Let the chocolate sit in the 95 degree water for about 15 minutes for it to come to temp.
